<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-24T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-24T06:00:00-05:00" n="58" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/1410: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-24T19:00:00+08:00">January 24, 1938—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 24—12:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>54. Allison’s 33, January 22, 4 p.m. I have replied as follows.</p>
                            <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“January 24, 5 p.m. Your 33, January 22, 4 p.m. I see no reason
                                    why you should not approach Japanese military with a view to
                                    urging that International Committee be permitted to import
                                    supplies. I have repeated this telegram to Washington and
                                    Tokyo”.</p>
                            </quote>
                            <p>Repeated to Shanghai, Shanghai please repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>